var documenterSearchIndex = {"docs":
[{"category":"section","location":"introduction/#Introduction","page":"Introduction","text":"ISOKANN.jl learns slow reaction coordinates (χ, \"chi\") as eigenfunctions of the Koopman operator from short trajectory data. This page covers the data model, the training loop, and the handful of types you will use most.","title":"Introduction"},{"category":"section","location":"introduction/#The-data-model","page":"Introduction","text":"ISOKANN needs two kinds of samples:\n\nxs: a matrix of shape (d, n) — n starting points in a d-dimensional state or feature space.\nys: a 3-D array of shape (d, nk, n) — for each starting point in xs, nk Koopman replicas obtained by propagating the dynamics with a common lag time.\n\nThese are used to estimate the action of the Koopman operator via a Monte-Carlo approximation,\n\nKchi(x) = mathbbE_X_0 = x chi(X_t) approx frac1N sum_i=1^N chi(y_i)\n\nThe starting points can be sampled arbitrarily (they do not need to come from the stationary distribution), but the learned χ can only represent the part of the dynamics covered by xs. The ys must be propagated from the corresponding xs under the system's dynamics with a common lag time.","title":"The data model"},{"category":"section","location":"introduction/#Minimal-example","page":"Introduction","text":"For raw (xs, ys) data you can construct an Iso directly:\n\nusing ISOKANN\n\nxs = rand(3, 100)\nys = rand(3, 10, 100)\niso = Iso((xs, ys))\nrun!(iso, 100)   # 100 ISOKANN iterations\nchis(iso)        # learned χ values","title":"Minimal example"},{"category":"section","location":"introduction/#Using-a-simulation","page":"Introduction","text":"For adaptive sampling and for bookkeeping the link between coordinates and network features, wrap the dynamics in a SimulationData:\n\nusing ISOKANN\n\nsim  = Doublewell()                        # 1D analytical potential\ndata = SimulationData(sim, 100, 10)        # 100 starting points, 10 Koopman samples each\niso  = Iso(data)\nrun!(iso, 100)\nchis(iso)\n\nBuilt-in simulations include Doublewell, Triplewell, MuellerBrown, Diffusion (general Langevin dynamics) and OpenMMSimulation (molecular dynamics via OpenMM). You can also plug in your own dynamics by implementing the IsoSimulation interface (at minimum propagate) or provide externally-generated trajectories via ExternalSimulation / data_from_trajectory.","title":"Using a simulation"},{"category":"section","location":"introduction/#OpenMM-quick-start","page":"Introduction","text":"using ISOKANN\n\nsim  = OpenMMSimulation()                  # bundled alanine dipeptide\ndata = SimulationData(sim, 100, 5)\niso  = Iso(data)\n\nrun!(iso, 100)                             # or: run_kde!(iso; generations=5, iter=100)\n\nplot_training(iso)\nscatter_ramachandran(iso)\nrates(iso)                                 # macro-state transition rates\nsave_reactive_path(iso, out=\"path.pdb\")","title":"OpenMM quick start"},{"category":"section","location":"introduction/#Classical-ISOKANN-on-precomputed-trajectories","page":"Introduction","text":"If you already have trajectory data and just want to run ISOKANN on it (no new sampling), turn your trajectories into (xs, ys) pairs with data_from_trajectory (single trajectory) or data_from_trajectories (many). Both support stride, lag, and reverse (treat the trajectory as time-reversible, which doubles the data):\n\n# single trajectory of shape (d, nframes)\ndata = SimulationData(sim, data_from_trajectory(xs; lag=10, stride=1))\n\n# many trajectories of varying length\ndata = SimulationData(sim, data_from_trajectories([xs1, xs2, ...]; lag=10))\n\n# or, if you have no `sim` and only raw arrays\ndata = SimulationData(xs, ys)\n\nFor OpenMM trajectories on disk, load_trajectory / readchemfile return a (d, nframes) coordinate matrix ready to pass into data_from_trajectory.","title":"Classical ISOKANN on precomputed trajectories"},{"category":"section","location":"introduction/#What-the-pieces-do","page":"Introduction","text":"Iso is the main training object. It holds the neural network, the optimizer, training data, the target transform, and loss/log history.\nSimulationData wraps an IsoSimulation together with its sampled coords and the derived features that are actually fed into the network. The mapping coords → features is defined by the simulation's featurizer (for OpenMMSimulation the default is pairwise distances, selectable between all atoms, locally close atoms, or only C-α atoms; see its docstring).\nTraining is driven by run!. Each iteration computes a target from E[χ(ys)] via a configurable transform (TransformShiftscale for 1-D χ, TransformISA / TransformPseudoInv for multi-dim χ) and takes a batch of gradient steps against ‖model(xs) − target‖².\nAdaptive sampling is available via run_kde!, which interleaves KDE-based resampling along the current χ with training. (The older runadaptive! is a deprecated alias.)\nResults: chis returns the learned χ values, rates returns the macro-state transition rate matrix, save_reactive_path writes a PDB of the extracted reaction path.","title":"What the pieces do"},{"category":"section","location":"introduction/#Accessing-data","page":"Introduction","text":"SimulationData lets you reach either view of the samples:\n\ncoords / propcoords — raw xs / ys coordinates.\nfeatures / propfeatures — featurized xs / ys actually passed to the network.","title":"Accessing data"},{"category":"section","location":"introduction/#Source-layout","page":"Introduction","text":"Core:\n\nsrc/iso.jl — the Iso type and the training loop (run!, run_kde!)\nsrc/simulation.jl — SimulationData and the IsoSimulation interface\nsrc/data.jl — low-level operations on the (xs, ys) tuple\nsrc/isotarget.jl — ISOKANN target transforms (1-D and multi-dim)\nsrc/models.jl — default networks and optimizers\n\nSimulators:\n\nsrc/simulators/langevin.jl — analytical potentials (Doublewell, Triplewell, MuellerBrown) integrated via StochasticDiffEq\nsrc/simulators/openmm.jl — OpenMM wrapper (through PythonCall)\nsrc/simulators/bridge.jl — guided Langevin bridges toward target χ values\nsrc/simulators/metadynamics.jl — draft metadynamics implementation\n\nUtilities:\n\nsrc/molutils.jl — alignment, dihedrals, and other molecular helpers\nsrc/pairdists.jl — pairwise-distance features\nsrc/plots.jl — training / χ plots\nsrc/subsample.jl — stratified and KDE-based subsampling\nsrc/reactionpath.jl, src/reactionpath2.jl — reaction-path extraction","title":"Source layout"},{"category":"section","location":"installation/#Installation","page":"Installation","text":"","title":"Installation"},{"category":"section","location":"installation/#Julia","page":"Installation","text":"Install Julia (v1.11 or newer) with juliaup:\n\ncurl -fsSL https://install.julialang.org | sh\n\nAfter restarting your shell, julia starts the REPL.","title":"Julia"},{"category":"section","location":"installation/#ISOKANN","page":"Installation","text":"In the REPL, enter package mode (type ]) and add the release version:\n\npkg> add ISOKANN\npkg> test ISOKANN\n\nFor the latest development version:\n\npkg> add https://github.com/axsk/ISOKANN.jl\n\nIf you are new to Julia, take a moment to read about Pkg environments; ISOKANN is most convenient when used inside a project environment.\n\nThe first run precompiles a sizeable dependency tree — expect a few minutes.","title":"ISOKANN"},{"category":"section","location":"installation/#OpenMM-(for-molecular-dynamics)","page":"Installation","text":"Since v2.0, ISOKANN calls OpenMM through PythonCall.jl, and Python dependencies are managed by CondaPkg.jl. Installing ISOKANN should bring OpenMM, joblib, and openmmforcefields in automatically — no manual PyCall/Conda build step is needed.\n\nIf you want the same conda environment available from a Python shell too (e.g. to use the Python bindings in python/), point your tooling at the environment CondaPkg provisions (typically under .CondaPkg/env/), or share a single conda environment via CondaPkg's CONDAPKG_BACKEND / shared-env settings.\n\nFor troubleshooting, see the CondaPkg and PythonCall docs, or open an issue on the ISOKANN repository.","title":"OpenMM (for molecular dynamics)"},{"category":"section","location":"installation/#Development","page":"Installation","text":"To hack on ISOKANN itself:\n\ngit clone git@github.com:axsk/ISOKANN.jl.git\ncd ISOKANN.jl\njulia --project=.\n\nThen inside Julia:\n\npkg> instantiate\n\nWe strongly recommend loading Revise before ISOKANN so edits take effect without restarting:\n\nusing Revise\nusing ISOKANN\n\nSee the Julia Pkg docs for a deeper tour of environments and development workflows.","title":"Development"},{"category":"section","location":"installation/#Editor","page":"Installation","text":"VS Code with the Julia extension works well. On a remote machine, the Remote-SSH / Remote Coder extensions let you drive the same setup locally. The package is designed around interactive use in the REPL, so keep one open alongside your editor.","title":"Editor"},{"category":"section","location":"installation/#GPU","page":"Installation","text":"Training and most analysis routines run on CUDA GPUs via Flux/Functors. Move an Iso to and from GPU with gpu(iso) / cpu(iso). The OpenMM simulation itself selects its own platform (CPU/CUDA/OpenCL) via OpenMM's platform mechanism.","title":"GPU"},{"category":"section","location":"#ISOKANN.jl","page":"ISOKANN.jl","text":"Documentation for ISOKANN.jl.\n\nStart with the Introduction for an overview of the data model and training loop. The Installation page walks through getting Julia and OpenMM set up, and Tips covers practical choices like optimizer and regularization.","title":"ISOKANN.jl"},{"category":"section","location":"#Main-entry-points","page":"ISOKANN.jl","text":"","title":"Main entry points"},{"category":"section","location":"#Data-construction-and-manipulation","page":"ISOKANN.jl","text":"","title":"Data construction and manipulation"},{"category":"section","location":"#Models-and-Optimizers","page":"ISOKANN.jl","text":"","title":"Models and Optimizers"},{"category":"section","location":"#Public-API","page":"ISOKANN.jl","text":"","title":"Public API"},{"category":"section","location":"#Internal-API","page":"ISOKANN.jl","text":"","title":"Internal API"},{"category":"type","location":"#ISOKANN.Iso","page":"ISOKANN.jl","text":"Iso(data; opt=NesterovRegularized(), model=defaultmodel(data), gpu=false, kwargs...)\n\n\n\n\n\nIso(sim::IsoSimulation; nx=100, nk=10, nd=1, kwargs...)\n\nConvenience constructor which generates the SimulationData from the simulation sim and constructs the Iso object. See also Iso(data; kwargs...)\n\nArguments\n\nsim::IsoSimulation: The IsoSimulation object.\nnx::Int: The number of starting points.\nnk::Int: The number of koopman samples.\nnout::Int: Dimension of the χ function.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ISOKANN.Iso"},{"category":"type","location":"#ISOKANN.SimulationData","page":"ISOKANN.jl","text":"struct SimulationData{S,D,C,F}\n\nA struct combining a simulation with the simulated coordinates and corresponding ISOKANN trainingsdata\n\nFields\n\nsim::S: The simulation object.\ndata::D: The ISOKANN trainings data.\ncoords::C: The orginal coordinates of the simulations.\nfeaturizer::F: A function mapping coordinates to ISOKANN features.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ISOKANN.SimulationData"},{"category":"type","location":"#ISOKANN.OpenMM.OpenMMSimulation","page":"ISOKANN.jl","text":"OpenMMSimulation(; pdb, steps, ...)\nOpenMMSimulation(; py, steps)\n\nConstructs an OpenMM simulation object. Either use  OpenMMSimulation(;py, steps) where pyis the location of a .py python script creating a OpenMM simulation object or supply a .pdb file viapdb` and the following parameters (see also defaultsystem):\n\nArguments\n\npdb::String: Path to the PDB file.\nligand::String: Path to ligand file.\nforcefields::Vector{String}: List of force field XML files.\ntemp::Float64: Temperature in Kelvin.\nfriction::Float64: Friction coefficient in 1/picosecond.\nstep::Float64: Integration step size in picoseconds.\nsteps::Int: Number of simulation steps.\nfeatures: Which features to use for learning the chi function.             -  A vector of Int denotes the indices of all atoms to compute the pairwise distances from.             -  A vector of CartesianIndex{2} computes the specific distances between the atom pairs.             -  A number denotes the radius below which all pairs of atoms will be used (computed only on the starting configuration)             -  If nothing all pairwise distances are used.\nminimize::Bool: Whether to perform energy minimization on first state.\nnthreads: The number of threads to use for parallelization of multiple simulations.\nmmthreads: The number of threads to use for each OpenMM simulation. Set to \"gpu\" to use the GPU platform.\n\nReturns\n\nOpenMMSimulation: An OpenMMSimulation object.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ISOKANN.OpenMM.OpenMMSimulation"},{"category":"function","location":"#ISOKANN.propagate","page":"ISOKANN.jl","text":"propagate(sim::OpenMMSimulation, x0::AbstractMatrix, nk)\n\nPropagates nk replicas of the OpenMMSimulation sim from the inintial states x0.\n\nArguments\n\nsim: An OpenMMSimulation object.\nx0: Matrix containing the initial states as columns\nnk: The number of replicas to create.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ISOKANN.propagate"},{"category":"function","location":"#ISOKANN.run!","page":"ISOKANN.jl","text":"run!(iso::Iso, n=1, epochs=1)\n\nRun the training process for the Iso model.\n\nArguments\n\na iso::Iso: The Iso model to train.\n\nn::Int: The number of (outer) Koopman iterations.\nepochs::Int: The number of (inner) epochs to train the model for each Koopman evaluation.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ISOKANN.run!"},{"category":"function","location":"#ISOKANN.run_kde!","page":"ISOKANN.jl","text":"run_kde!(iso; generations=1, iter=100, cutoff=Inf, kde=1, unique=true)\n\nTrain iso with adaptive sampling. Sample kde new data points followed by iter isokann iterations and repeat this generations times. cutoff specifies the maximal data size, after which new data overwrites the oldest data. unique enforces resampling from yet unsampled ys only.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ISOKANN.run_kde!"},{"category":"function","location":"#ISOKANN.chis","page":"ISOKANN.jl","text":"chis(iso::Iso, data=iso.data)\n\nEvaluate the learned χ function on data (a SimulationData or a raw (xs, ys) tuple). Returns a (nout, n) matrix whose columns are the χ values at the starting points. Defaults to iso's own training data.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ISOKANN.chis"},{"category":"function","location":"#ISOKANN.rates","page":"ISOKANN.jl","text":"rates(iso::Iso)\n\nReturn the coarse grained rate matrix Q satisfying Kχ = exp(τQ)χ\n\nIn the 1D ISOKANN case return the rates for χ and 1-χ.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ISOKANN.rates"},{"category":"function","location":"#ISOKANN.plot_training","page":"ISOKANN.jl","text":"plot_training(iso; maxpoints=0)\n\nSummary dashboard of an Iso training run: loss history, learned χ values, and a scatter of χ vs. its training-target fix point. maxpoints caps the number of points drawn in the scatter/χ plots (0 = all).\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ISOKANN.plot_training"},{"category":"function","location":"#ISOKANN.scatter_ramachandran","page":"ISOKANN.jl","text":"scatter_ramachandran(iso::Iso; kwargs...)\nscatter_ramachandran(x, z; kwargs...)\n\nRamachandran scatter: plots each configuration's backbone dihedrals (φ, ψ) coloured by χ. Accepts an Iso, a (coords, model) pair, or a coordinate matrix with explicit χ values. Extra kwargs are forwarded to Plots.scatter.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ISOKANN.scatter_ramachandran"},{"category":"function","location":"#ISOKANN.save_reactive_path","page":"ISOKANN.jl","text":"save_reactive_path(iso::Iso,\n    coords::AbstractMatrix=coords(iso.data) |> cpu;\n    sigma=1,\n    maxjump=1,\n    out=\"out/reactive_path.pdb\",\n    source=pdbfile(iso.data),\n    kwargs...)\n\nExtract and save the reactive path of a given iso.\n\nComputes the maximum likelihood path with parameter sigma along the given data points, aligns it and saves it to the out path.\n\nSee also reactive_path.\n\nArguments\n\niso::Iso: The Iso for which the reactive path is computed.\ncoords: The coordinates amongst which the shortest path is calculated\nfullcoords: The full coordinates which are used to save the computed path frames (defaults to coords).\nweights: A vector of weights applied to each atom of the coordinates, determining the relative weight for the distance calculations.\nout=\"out/reactive_path.pdb\": The output file path for saving the reactive path.\nsource: The source .pdb file providing the topology\nkwargs...: additional parameters passed to reactive_path.\n\nReturns\n\nids: The IDs of the reactive path.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ISOKANN.save_reactive_path"},{"category":"function","location":"#ISOKANN.data_from_trajectory","page":"ISOKANN.jl","text":"data_from_trajectory(xs::AbstractMatrix; reverse=true, stride=1, lag=1)\n\nGenerate the (x,y) data pairs for ISOKANN from the trajectory xs.\n\nstride controls the stride of the starting positions x and lag the lag for the end positions y in terms of trajectory frames. If reverse is true, construct also the time-reversed pairs (recomended for stable ISOKANN training).\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ISOKANN.data_from_trajectory"},{"category":"function","location":"#ISOKANN.data_from_trajectories","page":"ISOKANN.jl","text":"data_from_trajectories(xss::AbstractVector{<:AbstractMatrix}; kwargs...)\ndata_from_trajectories(xs::AbstractArray{<:Any,3}; kwargs...)\n\nGenerate training data (x, y) pairs for ISOKANN from trajectories by calling data_from_trajectory  on each and concatenating the results.\n\nSee data_from_trajectory for details on the keyword arguments (reverse, stride, lag).\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ISOKANN.data_from_trajectories"},{"category":"function","location":"#ISOKANN.mergedata","page":"ISOKANN.jl","text":"mergedata(d1::SimulationData, d2::SimulationData)\n\nMerge the data and features of d1 and d2, keeping the simulation and features of d1. Note that there is no check if simulation features agree.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ISOKANN.mergedata"},{"category":"function","location":"#ISOKANN.addcoords!","page":"ISOKANN.jl","text":"addcoords!(iso::Iso, coords::AbstractMatrix)\naddcoords!(iso::Iso, n::Integer)\n\nExtend iso's training data with new starting points and their freshly propagated Koopman samples. If coords is a matrix, use its columns as new starting points. If an integer n is given, continue a length-n lagged trajectory from the current last frame and split it into (xs, ys) pairs.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ISOKANN.addcoords!"},{"category":"function","location":"#ISOKANN.resample_kde!","page":"ISOKANN.jl","text":"resample_kde!(iso::Iso, ny; kwargs...)\n\nReplace/augment iso's data by drawing ny new starting points via KDE-based subsampling along the current χ, then propagating them. Used by run_kde! but also callable directly for custom training loops.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ISOKANN.resample_kde!"},{"category":"function","location":"#ISOKANN.laggedtrajectory","page":"ISOKANN.jl","text":"laggedtrajectory(sim::OpenMMSimulation, lags; steps=steps(sim), resample_velocities=true, kwargs...)\n\nGenerate a lagged trajectory for a given OpenMMSimulation. E.g. x0–x–x–x  for lags=3 and steps=2\n\nArguments\n\nsim::OpenMMSimulation: The simulation object.\nlags: The number of steps.\nsteps: The lagtime, i.e. number of steps to take in the simulation.\nresample_velocities: Whether to resample velocities according to Maxwell-Boltzman for each lag.\nkwargs...: Additional keyword arguments to pass to the trajectory function.\n\nReturns\n\nA matrix of lags samples which each have steps simulation-steps inbetween them.\n\n\n\n\n\nlaggedtrajectory(data::SimulationData, n) = laggedtrajectory(data.sim, n, x0=coords(data)[:, end])\n\nSimulate a trajectory comprising of n simulations from the last point in data\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ISOKANN.laggedtrajectory"},{"category":"function","location":"#ISOKANN.pairnet","page":"ISOKANN.jl","text":"Fully connected neural network with layers layers from n to nout dimensions. activation determines the activation function for each but the last layer lastactivation can be used to modify the last layers activation function \n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ISOKANN.pairnet"},{"category":"function","location":"#ISOKANN.densenet","page":"ISOKANN.jl","text":"densenet(; layers::Vector{Int}, activation=Flux.sigmoid, lastactivation=identity, layernorm=true) -> Flux.Chain\n\nConstruct a fully connected neural network (Flux.Chain) with customizable layer sizes, activations,  and optional input layer normalization.\n\nArguments\n\nlayers::Vector{Int}: List of layer dimensions. For example, [10, 32, 16, 1] creates a network with input size 10, two hidden layers of size 32 and 16, and an output layer of size 1.\nactivation: Activation function applied to all layers except the last. Defaults to Flux.sigmoid.\nlastactivation: Activation function for the final layer. Defaults to identity.\nlayernorm::Bool: Whether to prepend a Flux.LayerNorm layer to normalize the input. Defaults to true.\n\nReturns\n\nA Flux.Chain composed of dense layers (and optionally a leading LayerNorm).\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ISOKANN.densenet"},{"category":"function","location":"#ISOKANN.AdamRegularized","page":"ISOKANN.jl","text":"AdamRegularized(adam=1e-3, reg=1e-4)\n\nConstructs an optimizer that combines weight decay regularization with ADAM. Uses reg for the weight decay parameter and lr as the learning rate for ADAM. Note that this is different from AdamW (Adam+WeightDecay) (c.f. Decay vs L2 Reg.). \n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ISOKANN.AdamRegularized"},{"category":"function","location":"#ISOKANN.NesterovRegularized","page":"ISOKANN.jl","text":"NesterovRegularized(; lr=1e-3, reg=1e-4)\n\nConstructs an optimizer that combines weight decay regularization with Nesterov momentum. Uses reg for the weight decay parameter and lr as the learning rate for Nesterov acceleration. This worked well as alternative where ADAM had problems.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ISOKANN.NesterovRegularized"},{"category":"type","location":"#ISOKANN.ExternalSimulation","page":"ISOKANN.jl","text":"ExternalSimulation(; pdbfile=nothing, masses=nothing, lagtime=1, kwargs...)\n\nPlaceholder IsoSimulation for data that was sampled outside of ISOKANN. It stores metadata (topology, lagtime, masses, …) without the ability to propagate new samples — use it together with data_from_trajectory / data_from_trajectories and SimulationData to train on precomputed trajectories.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ISOKANN.ExternalSimulation"},{"category":"method","location":"#ISOKANN.Iso-Tuple{Any}","page":"ISOKANN.jl","text":"Iso(data; opt=NesterovRegularized(), model=defaultmodel(data), gpu=false, kwargs...)\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ISOKANN.Iso"},{"category":"method","location":"#ISOKANN.Iso-Tuple{ISOKANN.IsoSimulation}","page":"ISOKANN.jl","text":"Iso(sim::IsoSimulation; nx=100, nk=10, nd=1, kwargs...)\n\nConvenience constructor which generates the SimulationData from the simulation sim and constructs the Iso object. See also Iso(data; kwargs...)\n\nArguments\n\nsim::IsoSimulation: The IsoSimulation object.\nnx::Int: The number of starting points.\nnk::Int: The number of koopman samples.\nnout::Int: Dimension of the χ function.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ISOKANN.Iso"},{"category":"type","location":"#ISOKANN.MetadynamicsSimulation","page":"ISOKANN.jl","text":"MetadynamicsSimulation(sim, rc, mdstate, dt, height, sigma)\nMetadynamicsSimulation(iso; height=1f0, sigma=0.1f0, dt=600f0)\n\nWell-tempered metadynamics bias that can be used as a force in a Langevin simulation.\n\nThe bias potential is a sum of Gaussians deposited at visited reaction coordinate (RC) values. When called as md(x), it returns the negative gradient of the (well-tempered) bias with respect to the configuration x, suitable for use as an additive force.\n\nArguments\n\nsim: underlying IsoSimulation (provides temperature and propagation)\nrc: reaction coordinate function x -> z, mapping configuration to RC space\nmdstate: accumulated Gaussian centers — one of MetadynamicsState, MetadynamicsStateMatrix (GPU-optimized), or MetadynamicsStateGridded\nheight: Gaussian height\nsigma: Gaussian width in RC space\ndt: well-tempered offset temperature (ΔT); Inf for classic (untempered) metadynamics\n\nThe convenience constructor builds rc from chicoords(iso) and initializes mdstate from the current chi values of the Iso.\n\nSee also\n\ndeposit!, trajectory, wt_free_energy, plot_profile\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ISOKANN.MetadynamicsSimulation"},{"category":"method","location":"#ISOKANN.SimulationData-Tuple{ISOKANN.IsoSimulation, Int64, Int64}","page":"ISOKANN.jl","text":"SimulationData(sim::IsoSimulation, nx::Int, nk::Int; ...)\nSimulationData(sim::IsoSimulation, xs::AbstractMatrix, nk::Int; ...)\nSimulationData(sim::IsoSimulation, (xs,ys); ...)\nSimulationData(xs, ys; pdb=\"\", ...)  # for external simulation data\n\nGenerates SimulationData from a simulation with either\n\nnx initial points and nk Koopman samples\nxs as initial points and nk Koopman sample\nxs as inintial points and ys as Koopman samples\nxs and ys from external simulations\nxs a trajectory of an external simulation, implicitly computing ys via data_from_trajectory of succesive samples\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ISOKANN.SimulationData"},{"category":"function","location":"#ISOKANN.AdamRegularized-2","page":"ISOKANN.jl","text":"AdamRegularized(adam=1e-3, reg=1e-4)\n\nConstructs an optimizer that combines weight decay regularization with ADAM. Uses reg for the weight decay parameter and lr as the learning rate for ADAM. Note that this is different from AdamW (Adam+WeightDecay) (c.f. Decay vs L2 Reg.). \n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ISOKANN.AdamRegularized"},{"category":"method","location":"#ISOKANN.Doublewell-Tuple{}","page":"ISOKANN.jl","text":"Doublewell(; kwargs...)\n\n1-D overdamped Langevin dynamics in the double-well potential V(x) = (x² − 1)². Returns a Diffusion; kwargs are forwarded to it (e.g. sigma, dt, lagtime).\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ISOKANN.Doublewell"},{"category":"method","location":"#ISOKANN.MuellerBrown-Tuple{}","page":"ISOKANN.jl","text":"MuellerBrown(; kwargs...)\n\n2-D overdamped Langevin dynamics in the Müller–Brown potential — a standard test system with three metastable basins. Returns a Diffusion; kwargs are forwarded (e.g. sigma, dt, lagtime).\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ISOKANN.MuellerBrown"},{"category":"function","location":"#ISOKANN.NesterovRegularized-2","page":"ISOKANN.jl","text":"NesterovRegularized(; lr=1e-3, reg=1e-4)\n\nConstructs an optimizer that combines weight decay regularization with Nesterov momentum. Uses reg for the weight decay parameter and lr as the learning rate for Nesterov acceleration. This worked well as alternative where ADAM had problems.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ISOKANN.NesterovRegularized"},{"category":"method","location":"#ISOKANN.Triplewell-Tuple{}","page":"ISOKANN.jl","text":"Triplewell(; kwargs...)\n\n2-D overdamped Langevin dynamics in the triple-well potential of Metzner, Schütte, Vanden-Eijnden (2006). Returns a Diffusion; kwargs are forwarded (e.g. sigma, dt, lagtime).\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ISOKANN.Triplewell"},{"category":"method","location":"#ISOKANN.addcoords!-Tuple{Iso, Any}","page":"ISOKANN.jl","text":"addcoords!(iso::Iso, coords::AbstractMatrix)\naddcoords!(iso::Iso, n::Integer)\n\nExtend iso's training data with new starting points and their freshly propagated Koopman samples. If coords is a matrix, use its columns as new starting points. If an integer n is given, continue a length-n lagged trajectory from the current last frame and split it into (xs, ys) pairs.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ISOKANN.addcoords!"},{"category":"method","location":"#ISOKANN.addcoords-Tuple{SimulationData, AbstractMatrix}","page":"ISOKANN.jl","text":"addcoords(d::SimulationData, coords::AbstractMatrix) -> SimulationData\n\nPropagate coords under d.sim (reusing the existing nk and featurizer) and return a new SimulationData that concatenates the new (xs, ys) pairs onto d. Non-mutating counterpart to addcoords!.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ISOKANN.addcoords"},{"category":"method","location":"#ISOKANN.atom_indices-Tuple{String, String}","page":"ISOKANN.jl","text":"atom_indices(filename::String, selector::String) -> Vector{Int}\n\nReturn the 1-based atom indices matching an MDTraj selector expression (e.g. \"name CA\", \"backbone\", \"not element H\") applied to the topology loaded from filename. Useful to restrict features/alignment to a subset of atoms.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ISOKANN.atom_indices"},{"category":"function","location":"#ISOKANN.ca_rmsd","page":"ISOKANN.jl","text":"ca_rmsd(cainds, pdb=\"data/villin nowater.pdb\", pdbref=\"data/villin/1yrf.pdb\")\n\nReturns a ReactionCoordsRMSD object which is used to calculate the Root Mean Square Deviation (RMSD) of the provided C-alpha atoms.\n\nInputs:     - cainds: Indices of the C-alpha atoms to consider for the RMSD     - target: PDB File containing the target structure to which the RMSD is computed     - source: Alternative PDB File for the source coordinates in the case that the indices differ (i.e. when matching different topologies)\n\nExample:     rsmd = ca_rmsd(3:10, \"data/villin/1yrf.pdb\", \"data/villin nowater.pdb\")     rmsd(rand(300,10))\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ISOKANN.ca_rmsd"},{"category":"method","location":"#ISOKANN.chicoords-Tuple{Iso, Any}","page":"ISOKANN.jl","text":"chicoords(iso::Iso, xs)\n\nEvaluate χ at raw coordinates xs (a (d, n) matrix), running the simulation's featurizer first. Handles CPU/GPU placement automatically.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ISOKANN.chicoords"},{"category":"function","location":"#ISOKANN.chis-2","page":"ISOKANN.jl","text":"chis(iso::Iso, data=iso.data)\n\nEvaluate the learned χ function on data (a SimulationData or a raw (xs, ys) tuple). Returns a (nout, n) matrix whose columns are the χ values at the starting points. Defaults to iso's own training data.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ISOKANN.chis"},{"category":"method","location":"#ISOKANN.coords-Tuple{Iso}","page":"ISOKANN.jl","text":"coords(iso::Iso)       -> (xs, ys)\nfeatures(iso::Iso)     -> (features(xs), features(ys))\npropcoords(iso::Iso)   -> ys\npropfeatures(iso::Iso) -> features(ys)\n\nAccessors for the training data attached to iso. coords returns the raw simulation coordinates, features the featurized inputs actually passed to the network; the prop* variants return only the propagated (Koopman) samples.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ISOKANN.coords"},{"category":"method","location":"#ISOKANN.data_from_trajectories-Tuple{AbstractArray{<:Any, 3}}","page":"ISOKANN.jl","text":"data_from_trajectories(xss::AbstractVector{<:AbstractMatrix}; kwargs...)\ndata_from_trajectories(xs::AbstractArray{<:Any,3}; kwargs...)\n\nGenerate training data (x, y) pairs for ISOKANN from trajectories by calling data_from_trajectory  on each and concatenating the results.\n\nSee data_from_trajectory for details on the keyword arguments (reverse, stride, lag).\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ISOKANN.data_from_trajectories"},{"category":"method","location":"#ISOKANN.data_from_trajectory-Tuple{AbstractMatrix}","page":"ISOKANN.jl","text":"data_from_trajectory(xs::AbstractMatrix; reverse=true, stride=1, lag=1)\n\nGenerate the (x,y) data pairs for ISOKANN from the trajectory xs.\n\nstride controls the stride of the starting positions x and lag the lag for the end positions y in terms of trajectory frames. If reverse is true, construct also the time-reversed pairs (recomended for stable ISOKANN training).\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ISOKANN.data_from_trajectory"},{"category":"method","location":"#ISOKANN.densenet-Tuple{}","page":"ISOKANN.jl","text":"densenet(; layers::Vector{Int}, activation=Flux.sigmoid, lastactivation=identity, layernorm=true) -> Flux.Chain\n\nConstruct a fully connected neural network (Flux.Chain) with customizable layer sizes, activations,  and optional input layer normalization.\n\nArguments\n\nlayers::Vector{Int}: List of layer dimensions. For example, [10, 32, 16, 1] creates a network with input size 10, two hidden layers of size 32 and 16, and an output layer of size 1.\nactivation: Activation function applied to all layers except the last. Defaults to Flux.sigmoid.\nlastactivation: Activation function for the final layer. Defaults to identity.\nlayernorm::Bool: Whether to prepend a Flux.LayerNorm layer to normalize the input. Defaults to true.\n\nReturns\n\nA Flux.Chain composed of dense layers (and optionally a leading LayerNorm).\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ISOKANN.densenet"},{"category":"method","location":"#ISOKANN.flattenlast-Tuple{Any}","page":"ISOKANN.jl","text":"flattenlast(x)\n\nConcatenate all but the first dimension of x. Usefull to convert a tensor of samples into a matrix \n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ISOKANN.flattenlast"},{"category":"method","location":"#ISOKANN.laggedtrajectory-Tuple{SimulationData, Any}","page":"ISOKANN.jl","text":"laggedtrajectory(data::SimulationData, n) = laggedtrajectory(data.sim, n, x0=coords(data)[:, end])\n\nSimulate a trajectory comprising of n simulations from the last point in data\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ISOKANN.laggedtrajectory"},{"category":"method","location":"#ISOKANN.load_trajectory-Tuple{Any}","page":"ISOKANN.jl","text":"load_trajectory(filename; top=nothing, kwargs...)\n\nwrapper around Python's mdtraj.load(). Returns a (3 * natom, nframes) shaped array.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ISOKANN.load_trajectory"},{"category":"method","location":"#ISOKANN.localpdistinds-Tuple{AbstractMatrix, Any}","page":"ISOKANN.jl","text":"localpdistinds(coords::AbstractMatrix, radius)\n\nGiven coords of shape ( 3n x frames ) return the pairs of indices whose minimal distance along all frames is at least once lower then radius\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ISOKANN.localpdistinds"},{"category":"method","location":"#ISOKANN.mergedata-Tuple{SimulationData, SimulationData}","page":"ISOKANN.jl","text":"mergedata(d1::SimulationData, d2::SimulationData)\n\nMerge the data and features of d1 and d2, keeping the simulation and features of d1. Note that there is no check if simulation features agree.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ISOKANN.mergedata"},{"category":"method","location":"#ISOKANN.pairnet-Tuple{}","page":"ISOKANN.jl","text":"Fully connected neural network with layers layers from n to nout dimensions. activation determines the activation function for each but the last layer lastactivation can be used to modify the last layers activation function \n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ISOKANN.pairnet"},{"category":"method","location":"#ISOKANN.pdists-Union{Tuple{T}, Tuple{AbstractMatrix, Array{Tuple{T, T}, 1}}} where T","page":"ISOKANN.jl","text":"pdists(coords::AbstractArray, inds::Vector{<:Tuple})\n\nCompute the pairwise distances between the particles specified by the tuples inds over all frames in traj. Assumes a column contains all 3n coordinates.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ISOKANN.pdists"},{"category":"method","location":"#ISOKANN.picking-Tuple{Any, Any}","page":"ISOKANN.jl","text":"picking(X, n; dists = pairwise_one_to_many)\n\nThe picking algorithm, i.e. greedy farthest point sampling, for n points on the columns of X. A custom distance function (::Vector, ::Matrix)->(::Vector) may be passed through dists.\n\nReturns X[:,qs], i.e. the picked samples, their former indices qs and their distances d to all other points.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ISOKANN.picking"},{"category":"method","location":"#ISOKANN.plot_training-Tuple{Any}","page":"ISOKANN.jl","text":"plot_training(iso; maxpoints=0)\n\nSummary dashboard of an Iso training run: loss history, learned χ values, and a scatter of χ vs. its training-target fix point. maxpoints caps the number of points drawn in the scatter/χ plots (0 = all).\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ISOKANN.plot_training"},{"category":"method","location":"#ISOKANN.rates-Tuple{Iso}","page":"ISOKANN.jl","text":"rates(iso::Iso)\n\nReturn the coarse grained rate matrix Q satisfying Kχ = exp(τQ)χ\n\nIn the 1D ISOKANN case return the rates for χ and 1-χ.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ISOKANN.rates"},{"category":"function","location":"#ISOKANN.reactionpath_minimum","page":"ISOKANN.jl","text":"reactionpath_minimum(iso::Iso, x0; steps=100)\n\nCompute the reaction path by integrating ∇χ with orthogonal energy minimization.\n\nArguments\n\niso::Iso: The isomer for which the reaction path minimum is to be computed.\nx0: The starting point for the reaction path computation.\nsteps=100: The number of steps to take along the reaction path.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ISOKANN.reactionpath_minimum"},{"category":"method","location":"#ISOKANN.reactionpath_ode-Tuple{Any, Any}","page":"ISOKANN.jl","text":"reactionpath_ode(iso, x0; steps=101, extrapolate=0, orth=0.01, solver=OrdinaryDiffEq.Tsit5(), dt=1e-3, kwargs...)\n\nCompute the reaction path by integrating ∇χ as well as orth * F orthogonal to ∇χ where F is the original force field.\n\nArguments\n\niso::Iso: The isomer for which the reaction path minimum is to be computed.\nx0: The starting point for the reaction path computation.\nsteps=100: The number of steps to take along the reaction path.\nminimize=false: Whether to minimize the orthogonal to ∇χ before integration.\nextrapolate=0: How fast to extrapolate beyond χ 0 and 1.\north=0.01: The weight of the orthogonal force field.\nsolver=OrdinaryDiffEq.Tsit5(): The solver to use for the ODE integration.\ndt=1e-3: The initial time step for the ODE integration.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ISOKANN.reactionpath_ode"},{"category":"method","location":"#ISOKANN.reactive_path-Tuple{AbstractVector, AbstractMatrix}","page":"ISOKANN.jl","text":"reactive_path(xi::AbstractVector, coords::AbstractMatrix; sigma, minjump=0, maxjump=1, method=QuantilePath(0.05), normalize=false, sortincreasing=true)\n\nFind the maximum likelihood path (under the model of brownion motion with noise sigma) through coords with times xi. Supports either CPU or GPU arrays.\n\nArguments\n\ncoords:  (ndim x npoints) matrix of coordinates.\nxi: time coordinate of the npoints points\nsigma: spatial noise strength of the model.\nminjump, maxjump: lower and upper bound to the jump in time xi along the path. Tighter bounds reduce the computational cost.\nmethod: either FromToPath,  QuantilePath, FullPath or MaxPath, specifying the end points of the path\nnormalize: whether to normalize all coords first\nsortincreasing: return the path from lower to higher xi values\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ISOKANN.reactive_path"},{"category":"function","location":"#ISOKANN.readchemfile","page":"ISOKANN.jl","text":"readchemfile(source::String, steps=:) -> Matrix{Float32}\nreadchemfile(traj::Chemfiles.Trajectory, frames) -> Matrix{Float32}\n\nLoad trajectory coordinates via the Chemfiles library and return them as a (3*natoms, nframes) matrix in nanometers (converted from Å). steps / frames selects a subset of frames; passing an Int returns a single flattened frame. Useful to pipe external trajectories into data_from_trajectory.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ISOKANN.readchemfile"},{"category":"method","location":"#ISOKANN.resample_kde!-Tuple{Any, Any}","page":"ISOKANN.jl","text":"resample_kde!(iso::Iso, ny; kwargs...)\n\nReplace/augment iso's data by drawing ny new starting points via KDE-based subsampling along the current χ, then propagating them. Used by run_kde! but also callable directly for custom training loops.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ISOKANN.resample_kde!"},{"category":"method","location":"#ISOKANN.resample_kde-Tuple{Any, Any, Any}","page":"ISOKANN.jl","text":"resample_kde(xs, ys, n; kwargs...)\n\nReturn n indices of ys such that the corresponding points \"fill the gaps\" in the KDE of xs. For possible kwargs see kde_needles.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ISOKANN.resample_kde"},{"category":"method","location":"#ISOKANN.resample_kde-Tuple{SimulationData, Any, Any}","page":"ISOKANN.jl","text":"resample_kde(data::SimulationData, model, n; bandwith, unique)\n\nadd new samples to data by running new simulations starting at some ys (i.e. the propagated points) of data where these points are iteratively selected to be closest to the minimum of a KDE of the current chi values from xs. If unique is true, start simulations from point only where there were no simulations before. bandwith controls the bandwidth of the KDE.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ISOKANN.resample_kde"},{"category":"method","location":"#ISOKANN.restricted_localpdistinds-Tuple{Any, Any, Any}","page":"ISOKANN.jl","text":"restricted_localpdistinds(coords, radius, atoms)\n\nLike localdists, but consider only the atoms with index in atoms\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ISOKANN.restricted_localpdistinds"},{"category":"function","location":"#ISOKANN.run!-2","page":"ISOKANN.jl","text":"run!(iso::Iso, n=1, epochs=1)\n\nRun the training process for the Iso model.\n\nArguments\n\na iso::Iso: The Iso model to train.\n\nn::Int: The number of (outer) Koopman iterations.\nepochs::Int: The number of (inner) epochs to train the model for each Koopman evaluation.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ISOKANN.run!"},{"category":"method","location":"#ISOKANN.run_kde!-Tuple{Any}","page":"ISOKANN.jl","text":"run_kde!(iso; generations=1, iter=100, cutoff=Inf, kde=1, unique=true)\n\nTrain iso with adaptive sampling. Sample kde new data points followed by iter isokann iterations and repeat this generations times. cutoff specifies the maximal data size, after which new data overwrites the oldest data. unique enforces resampling from yet unsampled ys only.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ISOKANN.run_kde!"},{"category":"function","location":"#ISOKANN.save_reactive_path-2","page":"ISOKANN.jl","text":"save_reactive_path(iso::Iso,\n    coords::AbstractMatrix=coords(iso.data) |> cpu;\n    sigma=1,\n    maxjump=1,\n    out=\"out/reactive_path.pdb\",\n    source=pdbfile(iso.data),\n    kwargs...)\n\nExtract and save the reactive path of a given iso.\n\nComputes the maximum likelihood path with parameter sigma along the given data points, aligns it and saves it to the out path.\n\nSee also reactive_path.\n\nArguments\n\niso::Iso: The Iso for which the reactive path is computed.\ncoords: The coordinates amongst which the shortest path is calculated\nfullcoords: The full coordinates which are used to save the computed path frames (defaults to coords).\nweights: A vector of weights applied to each atom of the coordinates, determining the relative weight for the distance calculations.\nout=\"out/reactive_path.pdb\": The output file path for saving the reactive path.\nsource: The source .pdb file providing the topology\nkwargs...: additional parameters passed to reactive_path.\n\nReturns\n\nids: The IDs of the reactive path.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ISOKANN.save_reactive_path"},{"category":"method","location":"#ISOKANN.save_trajectory-Tuple{Any, AbstractMatrix}","page":"ISOKANN.jl","text":"save_trajectory(filename, coords::AbstractMatrix; top::String)\n\nsave the trajectory given in coords to filename with the topology provided by the file top using mdtraj.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ISOKANN.save_trajectory"},{"category":"function","location":"#ISOKANN.savecoords","page":"ISOKANN.jl","text":"savecoords(path::String, iso::Iso, coords::AbstractMatrix=coords(iso.data); sorted=true, aligned=true)\n\nSave the coordinates of the specified matrix of coordinates to a file, using the molecule in iso as a template. If sorted the sort the coordinates by their increasing χ value. If align then align each frame to the previous one.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ISOKANN.savecoords"},{"category":"method","location":"#ISOKANN.scatter_ramachandran-Tuple{Iso}","page":"ISOKANN.jl","text":"scatter_ramachandran(iso::Iso; kwargs...)\nscatter_ramachandran(x, z; kwargs...)\n\nRamachandran scatter: plots each configuration's backbone dihedrals (φ, ψ) coloured by χ. Accepts an Iso, a (coords, model) pair, or a coordinate matrix with explicit χ values. Extra kwargs are forwarded to Plots.scatter.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ISOKANN.scatter_ramachandran"},{"category":"method","location":"#ISOKANN.trajectory-Tuple{ISOKANN.AbstractLangevin}","page":"ISOKANN.jl","text":"trajectory(l::AbstractLangevin; T=lagtime(l), x0=randx0(l), save_start=false, saveat=lagtime(l), dt=dt(l)) generate a trajectory of length T, starting at x0 with stepsize dt, saving the output every saveat time. \n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ISOKANN.trajectory"},{"category":"method","location":"#ISOKANN.trajectorydata_bursts-Tuple{ISOKANN.IsoSimulation, Any, Any}","page":"ISOKANN.jl","text":"trajectorydata_bursts(sim::IsoSimulation, steps, nk; kwargs...)\n\nSimulate a single long trajectory of steps times the lagtime and start nk burst trajectories at each step for the Koopman samples.\n\nx0–-x––x–-     / |  / |     y y  y y\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ISOKANN.trajectorydata_bursts"},{"category":"method","location":"#ISOKANN.trajectorydata_linear-Tuple{ISOKANN.IsoSimulation, Any}","page":"ISOKANN.jl","text":"trajectorydata_linear(sim::IsoSimulation, steps; reverse=false, kwargs...)\n\nSimulate a single long trajectory of steps times the lagtime and use this \"chain\" to generate the corresponding ISOKANN data. If reverse is true, also add the time-reversed transitions\n\nx (<)–> x (<)–> x\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ISOKANN.trajectorydata_linear"},{"category":"method","location":"#ISOKANN.writechemfile-Tuple{Any, Matrix}","page":"ISOKANN.jl","text":"writechemfile(filename, data::Array{<:Any,2}; source)\n\nSave the coordinates in data to filename with source as template using the Chemfiles library\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ISOKANN.writechemfile"},{"category":"constant","location":"#ISOKANN.OpenMM.FORCE_AMBER","page":"ISOKANN.jl","text":"FORCE_AMBER\n\nForce-field XML list (amber14-all.xml) — vacuum / no solvent. Pass as the forcefields keyword to OpenMMSimulation.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ISOKANN.OpenMM.FORCE_AMBER"},{"category":"constant","location":"#ISOKANN.OpenMM.FORCE_AMBER_IMPLICIT","page":"ISOKANN.jl","text":"FORCE_AMBER_IMPLICIT\n\nAmber14 force field with an OBC2 implicit solvent model (amber14-all.xml + implicit/obc2.xml). Pass as the forcefields keyword to OpenMMSimulation.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ISOKANN.OpenMM.FORCE_AMBER_IMPLICIT"},{"category":"type","location":"#ISOKANN.OpenMM.FeaturesAll","page":"ISOKANN.jl","text":"Featurizer: pairwise distances between all atoms \n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ISOKANN.OpenMM.FeaturesAll"},{"category":"method","location":"#ISOKANN.OpenMM.FeaturesPairs-Tuple{OpenMMSimulation}","page":"ISOKANN.jl","text":"FeaturesPairs(pairs::Vector{Tuple{Int,Int}})\nFeaturesPairs(system; selector=\"all\", maxdist=Inf, maxfeatures=Inf)\n\nCreates a FeaturesPairs object from either:\n\na list of index pairs (Vector{Tuple{Int,Int}}) passed directly.\nan OpenMMSimulation or PDB file path (String), selecting atom pairs using MDTraj selector syntax (selector), optionally filtered by maxdist (in nm) and limited to maxfeatures randomly sampled pairs.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ISOKANN.OpenMM.FeaturesPairs"},{"category":"method","location":"#ISOKANN.OpenMM.atoms-Tuple{OpenMMSimulation}","page":"ISOKANN.jl","text":"atoms(sim::OpenMMSimulation)\n\nReturn the list of OpenMM atom objects (via PythonCall) from the simulation's topology. Useful for inspecting elements, residues, or indices when building custom featurizers.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ISOKANN.OpenMM.atoms"},{"category":"method","location":"#ISOKANN.coords-Tuple{OpenMMSimulation}","page":"ISOKANN.jl","text":"coords(sim::OpenMMSimulation)\nsetcoords(sim::OpenMMSimulation, coords)\n\nRead or write the OpenMM context's current particle positions as a flat 3*natoms vector in nanometers. coords returns the current state; setcoords overwrites it (e.g. to re-initialize before a propagation).\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ISOKANN.coords"},{"category":"method","location":"#ISOKANN.propagate-Tuple{OpenMMSimulation, AbstractMatrix, Any}","page":"ISOKANN.jl","text":"propagate(sim::OpenMMSimulation, x0::AbstractMatrix, nk)\n\nPropagates nk replicas of the OpenMMSimulation sim from the inintial states x0.\n\nArguments\n\nsim: An OpenMMSimulation object.\nx0: Matrix containing the initial states as columns\nnk: The number of replicas to create.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ISOKANN.propagate"},{"category":"method","location":"#ISOKANN.savecoords-Union{Tuple{T}, Tuple{Any, OpenMMSimulation}, Tuple{Any, OpenMMSimulation, AbstractArray{T}}} where T","page":"ISOKANN.jl","text":"savecoords(path, sim::OpenMMSimulation, coords::AbstractArray{T})\n\nSave the given coordinates in a .pdb file using OpenMM\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ISOKANN.savecoords"},{"category":"function","location":"#ISOKANN.trajectory","page":"ISOKANN.jl","text":"trajectory(sim::OpenMMSimulation{Nothing}, steps=steps(sim); saveevery=1, x0=coords(sim), resample_velocities=false, throw=false, showprogress=true, reclaim=true)\n\nSimulates the trajectory of an OpenMM simulation.\n\nArguments\n\nsim::OpenMMSimulation{Nothing}: The OpenMM simulation object.\nsteps: The number of steps to simulate. Defaults to the number of steps defined in the simulation object.\nsaveevery: Interval at which to save the trajectory. Defaults to 1.\nx0: Initial coordinates for the simulation. Defaults to the current coordinates of the simulation object.\nsample_velocities: Whether to sample velocities at the start of the simulation.\nresample_velocities: Whether to resample velocities after each saveevery steps. Defaults to false.\nthrow: Whether to throw an error if the simulation fails. If false it returns the trajectory computed so far. Defaults to false.\nshowprogress: Whether to display a progress bar during the simulation. Defaults to true.\nreclaim: Whether to reclaim CUDA memory before the simulation. Defaults to true.\n\nReturns\n\nThe trajectory of the simulation as a matrix of coordinates.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ISOKANN.trajectory"},{"category":"type","location":"#ISOKANN.DataTuple","page":"ISOKANN.jl","text":"DataTuple = Tuple{Matrix{T},Array{T,3}} where {T<:Number}\n\nWe represent data as a tuple of xs and ys.\n\nxs is a matrix of size (d, n) where d is the dimension of the system and n the number of samples. ys is a tensor of size (d, k, n) where k is the number of koopman samples.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ISOKANN.DataTuple"},{"category":"type","location":"#ISOKANN.IsoSimulation","page":"ISOKANN.jl","text":"abstract type IsoSimulation\n\nAbstract type representing an IsoSimulation. Should implement the methods coords, propagate, dim\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ISOKANN.IsoSimulation"},{"category":"method","location":"#ISOKANN.LazyTrajectory-Tuple{String}","page":"ISOKANN.jl","text":"LazyTrajectory(path::String)\n\nRepresents the trajectory path as matrix whose columns are lazily loaded from disk.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ISOKANN.LazyTrajectory"},{"category":"type","location":"#ISOKANN.MetadynamicsState","page":"ISOKANN.jl","text":"MetadynamicsState{T, V}\n\nVector-of-vectors storage for Gaussian centers.\n\nPerformance: CPU: OK | GPU: slow (~1000x) | Add center: O(1) push Best for: CPU-only, frequent center additions Dynamics: Exact\n\nSee also: MetadynamicsStateMatrix, MetadynamicsStateGridded\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ISOKANN.MetadynamicsState"},{"category":"type","location":"#ISOKANN.MetadynamicsStateGridded","page":"ISOKANN.jl","text":"MetadynamicsStateGridded{ITP}\n\nGrid-based approximation of bias potential with cubic spline interpolation.\n\nPerformance: CPU: very fast | GPU: N/A | Add center: unsupported Best for: 1D–2D rapid exploration (low-dim only) Dynamics: Approximate (spline interpolation)\n\nSee also: MetadynamicsState, MetadynamicsStateMatrix\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ISOKANN.MetadynamicsStateGridded"},{"category":"type","location":"#ISOKANN.MetadynamicsStateMatrix","page":"ISOKANN.jl","text":"MetadynamicsStateMatrix{T}\n\nMatrix storage (nrc × n_centers) for Gaussian centers — GPU-optimized.\n\nPerformance: CPU: fast | GPU: very fast | Add center: O(n) hcat Best for: GPU production runs Dynamics: Exact\n\nSee also: MetadynamicsState, MetadynamicsStateGridded\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ISOKANN.MetadynamicsStateMatrix"},{"category":"type","location":"#ISOKANN.ReactionCoordsRMSD","page":"ISOKANN.jl","text":"struct ReactionCoordsRMSD\n\nInstances of this object allow to compute the Root Mean Square Deviation (RMSD) to a part of a reference molecule. See also ca_rmsd.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ISOKANN.ReactionCoordsRMSD"},{"category":"type","location":"#ISOKANN.Stabilize","page":"ISOKANN.jl","text":"TransformStabilize(target, last=nothing)\n\nWraps another target and permutes its target to match the previous target\n\nCurrently we also have the stablilization (wrt to the model though) inside most Transforms. TODO: Decide which to keep\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ISOKANN.Stabilize"},{"category":"type","location":"#ISOKANN.TransformGramSchmidt2","page":"ISOKANN.jl","text":"TransformGramSchmidt()\n\nCompute the target through a Gram-Schmidt orthonormalisation.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ISOKANN.TransformGramSchmidt2"},{"category":"type","location":"#ISOKANN.TransformISA","page":"ISOKANN.jl","text":"TransformISA(permute)\n\nCompute the target via the inner simplex algorithm (without feasiblization routine). permute specifies whether to apply the stabilizing permutation \n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ISOKANN.TransformISA"},{"category":"type","location":"#ISOKANN.TransformPseudoInv","page":"ISOKANN.jl","text":"TransformPseudoInv(normalize, direct, eigenvecs, permute)\n\nCompute the target by approximately inverting the action of K with the Moore-Penrose pseudoinverse.\n\nIf direct==true solve chi * pinv(K(chi)), otherwise inv(K(chi) * pinv(chi))). eigenvecs specifies whether to use the eigenvectors of the schur matrix. normalize specifies whether to renormalize the resulting target vectors. permute specifies whether to permute the target for stability.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ISOKANN.TransformPseudoInv"},{"category":"type","location":"#ISOKANN.TransformShiftscale","page":"ISOKANN.jl","text":"TransformShiftscale()\n\nClassical 1D shift-scale (ISOKANN 1) \n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ISOKANN.TransformShiftscale"},{"category":"method","location":"#ISOKANN._pickclosestloop-Tuple{AbstractVector, AbstractVector}","page":"ISOKANN.jl","text":"scales with n=length(hs) \n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ISOKANN._pickclosestloop"},{"category":"method","location":"#ISOKANN.bootstrap-Tuple{ISOKANN.IsoSimulation, Any, Any}","page":"ISOKANN.jl","text":"bootstrap(sim, nx, ny)\n\ncompute initial data by propagating the molecules initial state to obtain the xs and propagating them further for the ys \n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ISOKANN.bootstrap"},{"category":"method","location":"#ISOKANN.centercoords-Tuple{Any}","page":"ISOKANN.jl","text":"centercoords any given states by shifting their individual 3d mean to the origin\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ISOKANN.centercoords"},{"category":"method","location":"#ISOKANN.chi_exit_rate-Tuple{Any, Any, Any}","page":"ISOKANN.jl","text":"compute the chi exit rate as per Ernst, Weber (2017), chap. 3.3 \n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ISOKANN.chi_exit_rate"},{"category":"method","location":"#ISOKANN.constrained_free_energy-Tuple{Iso, Any}","page":"ISOKANN.jl","text":"constrained_free_energy(iso, xs; sim, steps)\n\nCompute the free energy using Thermodynamic Integration.  Starting from the levelset samples xs orhtogonal simulations estimate the  mean force along χ, which is integrated to yield the PMF. \n\nArguments\n\niso the Iso object. xs  the starting points (which should be well distributed in state space). sim the simulation used for the orthongal sampling. steps the number of steps in each orthogonal simulation.\n\nReturns\n\nF the free energy energy surface of χ in kJ/mol up to an additive constant.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ISOKANN.constrained_free_energy"},{"category":"method","location":"#ISOKANN.delta_G-Tuple{Any, Any}","page":"ISOKANN.jl","text":"delta_G(PMF,chi_vals)\n\nConvenience function to compute free energy differences in a double well free energy surface.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ISOKANN.delta_G"},{"category":"method","location":"#ISOKANN.energyminimization_chilevel-Tuple{Any, Any}","page":"ISOKANN.jl","text":"energyminimization_chilevel(iso, x0; f_reltol=1e-3, alphaguess=1e-5, iterations=20, show_trace=false, skipwater=false, algorithm=Optim.GradientDescent, xtol=nothing)\n\nLocal energy minimization on the current levelset of the chi function\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ISOKANN.energyminimization_chilevel"},{"category":"method","location":"#ISOKANN.expectation-Tuple{Any, Any}","page":"ISOKANN.jl","text":"expectation(f, xs)\n\nComputes the expectation value of f over xs. Supports WeightedSamples through extra dispatch\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ISOKANN.expectation"},{"category":"function","location":"#ISOKANN.exportdata","page":"ISOKANN.jl","text":"exportdata(data::AbstractArray, model, sys, path=\"out/data.pdb\")\n\nExport data to a PDB file.\n\nThis function takes an AbstractArray data, sorts it according to the model evaluation, removes duplicates, transforms it to standard form and saves it as a PDB file  to path.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ISOKANN.exportdata"},{"category":"method","location":"#ISOKANN.fixperm-Tuple{Any, Any}","page":"ISOKANN.jl","text":"fixperm(new, old)\n\nPermutes the rows of new such as to minimize L1 distance to old.\n\nArguments\n\nnew: The data to match to the reference data.\nold: The reference data.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ISOKANN.fixperm"},{"category":"function","location":"#ISOKANN.flatpairdists","page":"ISOKANN.jl","text":"flatpairdists(x)\n\nAssumes each col of x to be a flattened representation of multiple 3d coords. Returns the flattened pairwise distances as columns.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ISOKANN.flatpairdists"},{"category":"method","location":"#ISOKANN.flattenfirst-Tuple{Any}","page":"ISOKANN.jl","text":"collapse the first and second dimension of the array A into the first dimension \n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ISOKANN.flattenfirst"},{"category":"method","location":"#ISOKANN.growmodel-Tuple{Any, Any}","page":"ISOKANN.jl","text":"Given a model and return a copy with its last layer replaced with given output dimension n \n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ISOKANN.growmodel"},{"category":"method","location":"#ISOKANN.inputdim-Tuple{Flux.Chain}","page":"ISOKANN.jl","text":"obtain the input dimension of a Flux model \n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ISOKANN.inputdim"},{"category":"method","location":"#ISOKANN.integrate_chi-Tuple{Any, Any}","page":"ISOKANN.jl","text":"integratechi(f, chivals)\n\nCumulative integral of the mean force with respect to χ using the trapezoid rule.\n\nArguments\n\nf The mean force. chi_vals The levelset χ values.\n\nReturns\n\nF the (rigid) free energy surface of χ.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ISOKANN.integrate_chi"},{"category":"method","location":"#ISOKANN.load-Tuple{String}","page":"ISOKANN.jl","text":"load(path::String, iso::Iso)\n\nLoad the Iso object from a JLD2 file Note that it will be loaded to the CPU, even if it was saved on the GPU. An OpenMMSimulation will be reconstructed anew from the saved pdb file.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ISOKANN.load"},{"category":"method","location":"#ISOKANN.local_mean_force-Tuple{Iso, Any, Any}","page":"ISOKANN.jl","text":"localmeanforce(iso, xs; sim, steps)\n\nCompute the free energy using Thermodynamic Integration.  Bins the samples into levelsets, computes the mean force along χ locally in every levelset. (Extremely extensive sampling necessary.)\n\nArguments\n\niso the Iso object. xs  the starting points (which should be well distributed in state space). nbins The number of bins/levelsets.\n\nReturns\n\nF the free energy surface of χ in kJ/mol up to an additive constant.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ISOKANN.local_mean_force"},{"category":"method","location":"#ISOKANN.marginal_free_energy-Tuple{Iso}","page":"ISOKANN.jl","text":" marginal_free_energy(iso::Iso;nbins)\n\nCompute the free energy from the density of chi values.\n\nArguments\n\niso the Iso object. nbins the number of bins of the histogram used for estimation.\n\nReturns\n\nF the free energy energy surface of χ in kJ/mol up to an additive constant.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ISOKANN.marginal_free_energy"},{"category":"function","location":"#ISOKANN.model_with_opt","page":"ISOKANN.jl","text":"convenience wrapper returning the provided model with the default AdamW optimiser \n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ISOKANN.model_with_opt"},{"category":"method","location":"#ISOKANN.outputdim-Tuple{Flux.Chain}","page":"ISOKANN.jl","text":"Obtain the output dimension of a Flux model \n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ISOKANN.outputdim"},{"category":"method","location":"#ISOKANN.pairdistfeatures-Tuple{AbstractVector}","page":"ISOKANN.jl","text":"pairdistfeatures(inds::AbstractVector)\n\nReturns a featurizer function which computes the pairwise distances between the particles specified by inds\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ISOKANN.pairdistfeatures"},{"category":"method","location":"#ISOKANN.pickclosest_sort-Tuple{AbstractVector, AbstractVector}","page":"ISOKANN.jl","text":"pickclosest(haystack, needles)\n\nReturn the indices into haystack which lie closest to needles without duplicates by removing haystack candidates after a match. Note that this is not invariant under pertubations of needles\n\nscales with n log(n) m where n=length(haystack), m=length(needles) \n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ISOKANN.pickclosest_sort"},{"category":"method","location":"#ISOKANN.picking_aligned-Tuple{AbstractMatrix, Integer}","page":"ISOKANN.jl","text":"picking_aligned(x::AbstractMatrix, m::Integer)\n\nThe picking algorithm using pairwise aligned distances, e.g. for molecular coordinates. Assumes the columnes of x to be vectors of size 3xN holding the cartesian coordinates.\n\nsee also picking()\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ISOKANN.picking_aligned"},{"category":"function","location":"#ISOKANN.plotatoms!","page":"ISOKANN.jl","text":"scatter plot of all first \"O\" atoms of the starting points xs as well as the \"O\" atoms from the koopman samples to the first point from ys\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ISOKANN.plotatoms!"},{"category":"function","location":"#ISOKANN.plotlossdata","page":"ISOKANN.jl","text":"combined plot of loss graph and current atoms \n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ISOKANN.plotlossdata"},{"category":"function","location":"#ISOKANN.reactionforce","page":"ISOKANN.jl","text":"reactionforce(iso, sim, x, direction, orth=1)\n\nCompute the vector f with colinear component to dchi/dx such that dchi/dx * f = 1 and orth*forcefield in the orthogonal space\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ISOKANN.reactionforce"},{"category":"method","location":"#ISOKANN.realsubspace-Tuple{Any}","page":"ISOKANN.jl","text":"computation of the real invariant subspace from complex eigenvectors \n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ISOKANN.realsubspace"},{"category":"function","location":"#ISOKANN.resample_kde_ash","page":"ISOKANN.jl","text":"resample_kde_ash(xs, ys, n=10; m=20, target=Distributions.Uniform())\n\nPick n indices iys of the samples ys such that [xs; ys[iys]] approximates the target distribution. Approximates the density through an AverageShiftedHistogram on the range rng with window width m.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ISOKANN.resample_kde_ash"},{"category":"method","location":"#ISOKANN.resample_strat-Tuple{SimulationData, Any, Any}","page":"ISOKANN.jl","text":"resample_strat(d::SimulationData, model, n)\n\nχ-stratified subsampling. Select n samples amongst the provided ys/koopman points of d such that their χ-value according to model is approximately uniformly distributed and propagate them. Returns a new SimulationData which has the new data appended.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ISOKANN.resample_strat"},{"category":"method","location":"#ISOKANN.sample_coords-Tuple{Iso, Any}","page":"ISOKANN.jl","text":"function sample_coords(iso,n_points;xs)\n\nConvenience function to uniformly sample npoints out of the χ distribution of xs coordinates.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ISOKANN.sample_coords"},{"category":"method","location":"#ISOKANN.save-Tuple{String, Iso}","page":"ISOKANN.jl","text":"save(path::String, iso::Iso)\n\nSave the complete Iso object to a JLD2 file \n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ISOKANN.save"},{"category":"method","location":"#ISOKANN.saveextrema-Tuple{String, Iso}","page":"ISOKANN.jl","text":"saveextrema(path::String, iso::Iso)\n\nSave the two extermal configurations (metastabilities) to the file path.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ISOKANN.saveextrema"},{"category":"method","location":"#ISOKANN.scatter_chifix-Tuple{Any}","page":"ISOKANN.jl","text":"fixed point plot, i.e. x vs model(x) \n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ISOKANN.scatter_chifix"},{"category":"method","location":"#ISOKANN.selectrows-Tuple{Any, Any}","page":"ISOKANN.jl","text":"given an array of arbitrary shape, select the rows inds in the first dimension \n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ISOKANN.selectrows"},{"category":"method","location":"#ISOKANN.simulationtime-Tuple{SimulationData}","page":"ISOKANN.jl","text":"simulationtime(iso::Iso)\n\nprint and return the total simulation time contained in the data of iso in nanoseconds.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ISOKANN.simulationtime"},{"category":"method","location":"#ISOKANN.sqpairdist-Tuple{AbstractArray{<:Any, 3}}","page":"ISOKANN.jl","text":"sqpairdist(x::AbstractArray)\n\nCompute the squared pairwise distances between the columns of x. If x has 3 dimensions, the computation is batched along the 3rd dimension.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ISOKANN.sqpairdist"},{"category":"method","location":"#ISOKANN.subsample-Tuple{Any, AbstractMatrix, Any}","page":"ISOKANN.jl","text":"subsample(model, data::Array, n) :: Matrix\nsubsample(model, data::Tuple, n) :: Tuple\n\nSubsample n points of data uniformly in model. If model returns multiple values per sample, subsample along each dimension.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ISOKANN.subsample"},{"category":"method","location":"#ISOKANN.subsample-Tuple{Any, Any}","page":"ISOKANN.jl","text":"subsample(data, nx)\n\nreturn a random subsample of nx points from data \n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ISOKANN.subsample"},{"category":"method","location":"#ISOKANN.subsample_inds-Tuple{Any, Any, Any}","page":"ISOKANN.jl","text":"subsample_inds(model, xs, n) :: Vector{Int}\n\nReturns n indices of xs such that model(xs[inds]) is approximately uniformly distributed.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ISOKANN.subsample_inds"},{"category":"method","location":"#ISOKANN.subsample_uniformgrid-Tuple{Any, Any}","page":"ISOKANN.jl","text":"subsbample_uniformgrid(ys, n) -> is\n\ngiven a list of values ys, return nindicesissuch thatys[is]` are approximately uniform by picking the closest points to a randomly perturbed grid in [0,1].\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ISOKANN.subsample_uniformgrid"},{"category":"method","location":"#ISOKANN.updatehistory-Union{Tuple{T}, Tuple{T, Any}} where T","page":"ISOKANN.jl","text":"updatehistory(L, l)\n\nInsert the newest observations l of size (n,d) into columns 2:d+1 of the history matrix L of size (n,h). Automatically grow the n dimension of L if l is bigger.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ISOKANN.updatehistory"},{"category":"type","location":"#ISOKANN.OpenMM.FeaturesAtoms","page":"ISOKANN.jl","text":"Pairwise distances between all provided atoms \n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ISOKANN.OpenMM.FeaturesAtoms"},{"category":"method","location":"#ISOKANN.OpenMM.featurepairs-Tuple{SimulationData}","page":"ISOKANN.jl","text":"featurepairs(d::ISOKANN.SimulationData)\n\nreturns pairs of atom indices corresponding to the pairwise distance features \n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ISOKANN.OpenMM.featurepairs"},{"category":"method","location":"#ISOKANN.OpenMM.integrate_girsanov-Tuple{OpenMMSimulation}","page":"ISOKANN.jl","text":"integrate_girsanov(sim::OpenMMSimulation; x0=coords(sim), steps=steps(sim), bias, reclaim=true)\n\nIntegrate overdamped Langevin dynamics while computing Girsanov weights for a given bias:\n\nXt = F dt + σ u dt + sigma dBt\nwhere F = force(sim, Xt), σ = sqrt(2 kB T / (γ M)), u = bias(Xt; t, sigma, F)\n\nArguments\n\nsim::OpenMMSimulation : The simulation object.\nx0 : Initial coordinates (default: coords(sim)).\nsteps : Number of integration steps (default: steps(sim)).\nbias : Function x -> u that returns the bias u for the Girsanov reweighting (note that the actual force perturbation is sigma * u).\nreclaim : Whether to preallocate memory for performance.\n\nReturns\n\nx : Final coordinates.\ng : Cumulative Girsanov weight (logarithmic).\nz : Full trajectory of positions.\n\nNotes\n\nThe method assumes overdamped Langevin dynamics and accumulates the corresponding Girsanov weight g.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ISOKANN.OpenMM.integrate_girsanov"},{"category":"function","location":"#ISOKANN.OpenMM.integrate_langevin","page":"ISOKANN.jl","text":"integrate_langevin(sim::OpenMMSimulation, x0=coords(sim); steps=steps(sim), perturbation!::Union{Function,Nothing}=nothing, saveevery::Union{Int,Nothing}=nothing, reclaim=true)\n\nPerform standard Langevin dynamics integration for a given system.\n\nArguments\n\nsim::OpenMMSimulation : The simulation object with system parameters.\nx0 : Initial coordinates (default: coords(sim)).\nsteps : Number of integration steps (default: steps(sim)).\nperturbation! : Optional function (F, x) -> nothing to perturb the force F in-place.\nsaveevery : Interval to save coordinates (default: saves only final state).\nreclaim : Whether to preallocate/reclaim memory for performance.\n\nReturns\n\nArray of positions: either the final positions or a trajectory if saveevery is specified.\n\nNotes\n\nUses a simple Euler-Maruyama step for (underdamped) Langevin dynamics with optional bias.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ISOKANN.OpenMM.integrate_langevin"},{"category":"method","location":"#ISOKANN.OpenMM.langevin_girsanov!-Tuple{OpenMMSimulation}","page":"ISOKANN.jl","text":"langevin_girsanov!(sim::OpenMMSimulation; steps=steps(sim), bias=sim.bias, saveevery=1, x0=coords(sim), resample_velocities=false, showprogress=true, throw=true, reclaim=true, sigmascaled=true, should_stop=nothing)\n\nPerform underdamped Langevin dynamics using the ABOBA integrator with Girsanov reweighting.\n\nArguments\n\nsim::OpenMMSimulation : Simulation object containing masses, friction, forces, and temperature.\nsteps : Number of integration steps (default: steps(sim)).\nbias : Function q; t, sigma, F -> B returning perturbation force for reweighting.\nsaveevery : Interval to save coordinates and weights (default: 1).\nx0 : Initial coordinates (default: coords(sim)).\nresample_velocities : If true, resample momenta when saving (invalidates Girsanov weights).\nshowprogress : Whether to show a progress bar.\nthrow : Whether to throw errors on invalid states.\nreclaim : Whether to preallocate memory for performance.\nsigmascaled : Whether the bias is scaled by the noise amplitude, i.e. whether the resulting force is σ * bias (true) or only bias (false) (default: true).\nshould_stop : Optional stopping criterion function called at save points with kwargs (; k, t, logw). Returns Bool to interrupt integration (default: nothing for no early stopping).\n\nReturns\n\nWeightedSamples containing:\nqs : Saved coordinates at intervals of saveevery.\nweights : Corresponding Girsanov weights exp(-g).\n\nNotes\n\nUses the ABOBA splitting scheme for stable underdamped Langevin integration.\nComputes Girsanov weights to account for the applied bias.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ISOKANN.OpenMM.langevin_girsanov!"},{"category":"method","location":"#ISOKANN.laggedtrajectory-Tuple{OpenMMSimulation, Any}","page":"ISOKANN.jl","text":"laggedtrajectory(sim::OpenMMSimulation, lags; steps=steps(sim), resample_velocities=true, kwargs...)\n\nGenerate a lagged trajectory for a given OpenMMSimulation. E.g. x0–x–x–x  for lags=3 and steps=2\n\nArguments\n\nsim::OpenMMSimulation: The simulation object.\nlags: The number of steps.\nsteps: The lagtime, i.e. number of steps to take in the simulation.\nresample_velocities: Whether to resample velocities according to Maxwell-Boltzman for each lag.\nkwargs...: Additional keyword arguments to pass to the trajectory function.\n\nReturns\n\nA matrix of lags samples which each have steps simulation-steps inbetween them.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ISOKANN.laggedtrajectory"},{"category":"method","location":"#ISOKANN.randx0-Tuple{OpenMMSimulation, Any}","page":"ISOKANN.jl","text":"generate n random inintial points for the simulation mm \n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ISOKANN.randx0"},{"category":"section","location":"tips/#Tips-and-tricks","page":"Tips and tricks","text":"","title":"Tips and tricks"},{"category":"section","location":"tips/#Choosing-an-optimizer-and-regularization","page":"Tips and tricks","text":"During the ISOKANN iteration we train a neural network to represent the current \"target\", i.e. our current estimate of the chi function (as computed by the isotarget function). For this supervised learning (essentially regression) task, we use a form of stochastic gradient descent that is performed by an optimizer from Flux.jl / Optimisers.jl\n\nIf the training is not converging it may be worthwile to test another optimizer. You can choose the optimizer during the construction of the Iso object through passing the keyword agument opt. The default is \n\nIso(opt=NesterovRegularized())\n\nwhich has proven to be more stable then the common Adam optimizer. To switch to Adam you may try opt=AdamRegularized().\n\nBoth these commands are convenience constructors for an OptimizerChain, combining the optimizer with regularization.\n\n(Tikhonov/L2) regularization is adding a penalty to the training loss proportional to the magnitude of the model weights, and thus enforcing simpler/smoother models and therefore penalizing overfitting.\n\nThe constructors for AdamRegularized and NesterovRegularized both provide argument to adjust both the learning rate and regularization:\n\nNesterovRegularized(lr=1e-3, reg=1e-4)\n\nIf your model seems to be overfitting you may want to try a higher regularization, e.g. a magnitude higher then the default,so 1e-3 instead of 1e-4.","title":"Choosing an optimizer and regularization"}]
}
